On March 11, foreign media reported that a research team in Milan, Italy, believes that the new pneumonia in Italy may be spread through Germany, rather than directly from China. That's because studies have shown that the gene sequencing of an earlier Italian strain of the new coronavirus matches that of a strain of the virus that first appeared in Germany in January.

Scientists have been searching for Italian patient zero since Feb. 21, when a new case of pneumonia was first reported in the northern region of Lombardy. Although the team in Milan has not yet fully identified patient zero, sequencing the genes of the earlier neocoronavirus showed that the virus matched the sequence of the new coronavirus in a case that appeared in Germany in January.

"The closest genetic sequence to an earlier virus in Italy came from a case that was infected in Munich, Germany, between January 19 and 22, " said Massimo Boutros Boutros-Ghali, head of the Infectious Diseases Research Team at the SALCO hospital in Milan. The earlier virus detected above is believed to be the "ancestor" of all viruses in Italy.

Boutros Boutros-Ghali added that the German patient had contracted the virus after contact with a person from China.

Boutros Boutros-Ghali said his team's analysis showed that the NCP epidemic had already occurred in Italy between January 25 and 26, that was long before the northern city of Codogno officially diagnosed its first patient in Italy.

"We can imagine a person (patient zero) coming into contact with an infected person in Munich and then going to Italy and spreading the virus 'without any symptoms' in Italy, " Boutros Boutros-Ghali said.
